[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(13) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Othniel.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:15-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is here added that he was Caleb’s younger brother. (See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 3:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) The Hebrew may mean either that Othniel was “son of Kenaz and brother of Caleb” (in which case he married his niece); or “son of Kenaz, who was Caleb’s brother” (as in “Jonadab, the son of Shimeah David’s brother,” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Samuel 13:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), in which case Achsah was his cousin. The Masoretes, to whom is due the punctuation, &c., of our Hebrew Scriptures, show by their pointing that they understood the words in the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "former ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "sense. But though Ben-kenaz may simply mean Kenezite (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 14:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 32:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), it is strange in that case that Othniel should never be called a son of Jephunneh. If he was a brother of Caleb’s, he must have lived to extreme old age, and have been an old man when he married Achsah. For the importance of Caleb’s family, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 27:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Rabbis identify Othniel with the Jabez who is so abruptly introduced in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 4:9-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and connect Achsah’s petition with the prayer there recorded; and they suppose that he founded the school of scribes at Jabez (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 2:55",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and was a teacher of law to the Kenites.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "1:9-20 The Canaanites had iron chariots; but Israel had God on their side, whose chariots are thousands of angels, Ps 68:17. Yet they suffered their fears to prevail against their faith. About Caleb we read in Jos 15:16-19. The Kenites had settled in the land. Israel let them fix where they pleased, being a quiet, contented people. They that molested none, were molested by none. Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Render \"and the children of Judah fought against Jerusalem, and took it, and smote it,\" etc. With regard to the capture of Jerusalem there is some obscurity. It is here said to have been taken, smitten with the edge of the sword, and burned, by the children of Judah. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 12:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 12:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the Jebusite and the king of Jerusalem are enumerated among Joshua's conquests, but without any distinct mention of the capture of the city; and in the marginal reference we read that the Jebusites were not expelled from Jerusalem, but dwelt with the children of Judah (compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 1:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Further, we learn from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 19:10-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that Jerusalem was wholly a Jebusite city in the lifetime of Phinehas ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 20:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and so it continued until the reign of David ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 5:6-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The conclusion is that Jerusalem was only taken once, namely, at the time here described, and that this was in the lifetime of Joshua; but that the children of Judah did not occupy it in sufficient force to prevent the return of the Jebusites, who gradually recovered complete possession.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Set the city on fire - A phrase found only at Judges 20:48; 2 Kings 8:12, and Psalm 74:7. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Set the city on fire - A phrase found only at ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Judges 20:48",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 8:12",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 74:7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "8. Now the children of Judah had fought against Jerusalem, and had taken it—The capture of this important city, which ranks among the early incidents in the war of invasion (Jos 15:63), is here noticed to account for its being in the possession of the Judahites; and they brought Adoni-bezek thither [Jud 1:7], in order, probably, that his fate being rendered so public, might inspire terror far and wide. Similar inroads were made into the other unconquered parts of Judah's inheritance [Jud 1:9-11]. The story of Caleb's acquisition of Hebron is here repeated (Jos 15:16-19). [See on [208]Jos 15:16.]",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
